GWAS accession identifier mapping

Source: R/id_mapping.R
identifier_mapping.Rd

Use these functions to map between identifiers of studies, associations, variants or traits. Each association_id maps to just one study_id; all other mappings are one-to-many. Moreover, in the case of the mapping of variant identifiers to trait identifiers (efo_id) the mapping is first performed from variant id to association id, and only then to trait identifier. All other mappings are direct in the sense that the Gwas Catalog REST API provides the endpoints that make those direct queries possible.

study_to_association(study_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

study_to_variant(study_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

study_to_trait(study_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

association_to_study(association_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

association_to_variant(association_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

association_to_trait(association_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

variant_to_study(variant_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

variant_to_association(variant_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

variant_to_trait(
  variant_id,
  keep_association_id = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE,
  warnings = TRUE
)

trait_to_study(efo_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

trait_to_association(efo_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

trait_to_variant(efo_id, verbose = FALSE, warnings = TRUE)

Arguments

study_id, association_id, variant_id, efo_id

A character vector of accession identifiers for either studies (study_id), associations (association_id), variants (variant_id) or traits (efo_id).
verbose

Whether the function should be verbose about the different queries or not.
warnings

Whether to print warnings.
keep_association_id

In the case of the variant_to_trait() function, the mapping from variant ids to EFO traits ids is performed via association ids; this option allow you to keep the association identifier in the final output (default is FALSE).

Value

A dataframe of two identifiers (three if keep_association_id is TRUE and if variant_to_trait() used). First column is the from identifier and the second column is the to identifier.

Examples

# Map GWAS study identifiers to association identifiers
study_to_association(c('GCST001084', 'GCST001085'))

#> # A tibble: 14 x 2
#>    study_id   association_id

#>  3 GCST001084 24300105

# Map GWAS study identifiers to variant identifiers

# Map GWAS study identifiers to EFO trait identifiers
study_to_trait(c('GCST001084', 'GCST001085'))

#> # A tibble: 2 x 2
#>   study_id   efo_id     
#>   <chr>      <chr>      
#> 1 GCST001084 EFO_0001645
#> 2 GCST001085 EFO_0000537

# Map GWAS association identifiers to study identifiers
association_to_study(c('24300097', '24299759'))

#> # A tibble: 2 x 2
#>   association_id study_id  
#>   <chr>          <chr>     
#> 1 24300097       GCST001084
#> 2 24299759       GCST001085

# Map GWAS association identifiers to variant identifiers
association_to_variant(c('24300097', '24299759'))

#> # A tibble: 4 x 2
#>   association_id variant_id
#>   <chr>          <chr>     
#> 1 24300097       rs11924705
#> 2 24300097       rs6789378 
#> 3 24299759       rs10496288
#> 4 24299759       rs10496289

# Map GWAS association identifiers to EFO trait identifiers
association_to_trait(c('24300097', '24299759'))

#> # A tibble: 2 x 2
#>   association_id efo_id     
#>   <chr>          <chr>      
#> 1 24300097       EFO_0001645
#> 2 24299759       EFO_0000537

# Map GWAS variant identifiers to study identifiers
variant_to_study(c('rs7904579', 'rs138331350'))

#> # A tibble: 2 x 2
#>   variant_id  study_id  
#>   <chr>       <chr>     
#> 1 rs7904579   GCST005387
#> 2 rs138331350 GCST007140

# Map GWAS variant identifiers to association identifiers
variant_to_association(c('rs7904579', 'rs138331350'))

#> # A tibble: 3 x 2
#>   variant_id  association_id
#>   <chr>       <chr>         
#> 1 rs7904579   27460811

#> 3 rs138331350 35840598      

# Map GWAS variant identifiers to EFO trait identifiers
variant_to_trait(c('rs7904579', 'rs138331350'))

#> # A tibble: 4 x 2
#>   variant_id  efo_id

# Map GWAS variant identifiers to EFO trait identifiers
